.TH io_ansi 3 "stdlib 7.3" "Ericsson AB" "Erlang Module Definition"
.SH NAME
io_ansi \- Controlling the terminal using virtual terminal sequences (aka [ANSI escape codes]).

.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
This module provides an interface to emit and parse virtual terminal sequences (VTS), also known as [ANSI escape codes]. VTS can be used to:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
change the style of text or background in the terminal by adding color or emphasis.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
delete printed characters or lines.

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
move, hide or show the cursor

.RE

.PP
and more things. As different terminals are interpret VTSs slightly differently, \fIio_ansi\fR uses the local [terminfo] database together with predefined sequences to emit the correct sequence for the terminal that is currently used. To fetch values directly from the [terminfo] database you can use \fItput/2\fR, \fItigetnum/1\fR and \fItigetflag/1\fR.

.PP
\fIio_ansi\fR provides two interfaces to emit sequences. You can either call the function representing the sequence you want to emit, for example \fIio_ansi:blue()\fR and it will return the sequence representing blue.

.IP
.nf
1> io_ansi:blue().
<<"\\e[34m">>

.fi

.PP
This will use the [terminfo] database locally where the call is made, so it may not be correct if used across nodes.

.PP
You can also use the \fIio_ansi:format/1,2,3\fR functions which works just as \fIio_lib:bformat/3\fR, except that it also accepts atoms and tuples that represent VTSs. For example:

.IP
.nf
1> io_ansi:format([blue,"~p"], [red]).
<<"\\e[34mred\\e(B\\e[m">>

.fi

.PP
\fIio_ansi:format/3\fR will automatically reset the terminal to its original state and strip any VTSs that are not supported by the terminal. It can also be disabled through an option. For example:

.IP
.nf
1> io_ansi:format([blue,"~p"], [red], [{enabled, false}]).
<<"red">>

.fi

.PP
Finally there is \fIio_ansi:fwrite/1,2,3,4\fR which does not return the string to be printed, but instead sends it to the \fIio:device/0\fR that should handle it. \fIio_ansi:fwrite/4\fR works across nodes and will use the [terminfo] database where the data is outputted to decide what to emit.

.PP
https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man5/terminfo.5.html https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ANSI_escape_code

