.SH FUNCTIONS
.LP
.B
\fBalternate_character_set_mode() -> unicode:chardata().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Enable the alternate characters set mode

.PP
Example:

.IP
.nf
1> io_ansi:alternate_character_set_mode().
<<"\\e(0">>
2> io_ansi:fwrite(["%%", alternate_character_set_mode, " tqqu\\n"]).
%% ├──┤
ok

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBalternate_character_set_mode_off() -> unicode:chardata().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Disable the alternate characters set mode

.PP
Example:

.IP
.nf
1> io_ansi:alternate_character_set_mode_off().
<<"\\e(B">>

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBalternate_screen() -> unicode:chardata().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Activate the alternate screen buffer.

.PP
The alternate screen buffer is a separate screen buffer that full-screen terminal applications (like \fIvim\fR, \fIless\fR, \fIhtop\fR, or \fIman\fR) use to display their content. When activated, the current screen content and cursor position are saved. When deactivated with \fIalternate_screen_off/0\fR, the original screen content is restored, making it appear as if the full-screen application was never there.

.PP
Example:

.IP
.nf
1> io_ansi:alternate_screen().
<<"\\e[?1049h\\e[22;0;0t">>

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBalternate_screen_off() -> unicode:chardata().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Deactivate the alternate screen.

.PP
Example:

.IP
.nf
1> io_ansi:alternate_screen_off().
<<"\\e[?1049l\\e[23;0;0t">>

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBbackground(Index :: 0..255 | 0..87 | color_atom()) ->\fR
\fB                    unicode:chardata().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Change background color to index color. \fIIndex\fR 0-15 are equivilant to the named colors in \fIbackground_color/0\fR in the order that they are listed.

.PP
Example:

.IP
.nf
1> io_ansi:background(2).
<<"\\e[42m">>
2> io_ansi:background(80).
<<"\\e[48;5;80m">>

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBbackground(0..255, 0..255, 0..255) -> unicode:chardata().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Change background color to RGB color.

.PP
Example:

.IP
.nf
1> io_ansi:background(255, 255, 0).
<<"\\e[48;2;255;255;0m">>

.fi


