\fBreverse_index() -> unicode:chardata().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Move the cursor up one line, but keeps the cursor on the same location on the screen by scrolling the screen down.

.PP
Example:

.IP
.nf
1> io_ansi:reverse_index().
<<"\\eM">>

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBscan(unicode:chardata()) ->\fR
\fB              [unicode:unicode_binary() |\fR
\fB               vts() |\fR
\fB               {csi, unicode:unicode_binary()}].\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Scan the string for virtial terminal sequences.

.PP
The recognized VTSs will be converted into the corresponding \fIvts/0\fR.

.PP
If you intend to parse arrow keys it is recommended that you first set the terminal in application mode by using \fIkeypad_transmit_mode/0\fR. This will make it easier for \fIio_ansi\fR to correctly detect arrow keys.

.PP
Any unrecognized control sequence introducers, will be placed in a tuple tagged with \fIcsi\fR.

.PP
Example:

.IP
.nf
1> io_ansi:scan("\\eOA").
[kcursor_up]
2> io_ansi:scan("\\eOB").
[kcursor_down]
3> io_ansi:scan(io_ansi:format([bold, "text"])).
[bold, ~"text", reset]
4> io_ansi:scan(io_ansi:format([{cursor, 0, 0}])).
[{csi, ~"\\e[1;1H"}, reset]

.fi


