.RE
.B
\fBtigetflag(TermInfoCapName :: string()) -> boolean().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns true if the terminfo capability is available, otherwise false.

.PP
The names of the terminal capabilities can be found in the terminfo documentation, or by calling \fItinfo/0\fR. \fItigetflag/1\fR will use the terminfo definition associated with the \fITERM\fR environment variable when the Erlang VM is started. It is not possible to change after startup.

.PP
Example:

.IP
.nf
1> io_ansi:tigetflag("xn").
true
2> io_ansi:tigetflag("foobar").
false

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBtigetnum(TermInfoCapName :: string()) -> -1 | non_neg_integer().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns the number representing a terminfo capability.

.PP
The names of the terminal capabilities can be found in the terminfo documentation, or by calling \fItinfo/0\fR. \fItigetnum/1\fR will use the terminfo definition associated with the \fITERM\fR environment variable when the Erlang VM is started. It is not possible to change after startup.

.PP
Returns \fI-1\fR if the capability is not available.

.PP
Example:

.IP
.nf
1> io_ansi:tigetnum("co").
80
2> io_ansi:tigetnum("foobar").
-1

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBtinfo() ->\fR
\fB               #{bool :=\fR
\fB                     [#{code := string(),\fR
\fB                        name := string(),\fR
\fB                        full_name := string()}]}.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns information about all available terminfo capabilities. See the terminfo documentation for details on each.

.PP
\fItinfo/0\fR will use the terminfo definition associated with the \fITERM\fR environment variable when the Erlang VM is started. It is not possible to change after startup.

.PP
When calling \fItput/2\fR, \fItigetnum/1\fR and \fItigetflag/1\fR you should provide the \fIname\fR of the capability you want.

.PP
Example:

.IP
.nf
1> io_ansi:tinfo().
#{ bool => [#{code => "xr",name => "OTxr",full_name => "return_does_clr_eol"} | ...],
   str => [#{code => "bx",name => "box1",full_name => "box_chars_1"} | ...],
   num => [#{code => "kn",name => "OTkn", full_name => "number_of_function_keys"} | ...]
 }

.fi


.RE
.B
\fBtput(TermInfoCapName :: string(), Args :: [integer()]) ->\fR
\fB              unicode:unicode_binary().\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Returns the string representing the action taken by the given terminal capability.

.PP
The names of the terminal capabilities can be found in the terminfo documentation, or by calling \fItinfo/0\fR. \fItput/2\fR will use the terminfo definition associated with the \fITERM\fR environment variable when the Erlang VM is started. It is not possible to change after startup.

.PP
If the given capability is not defined in the terminfo database an \fIenotsup\fR error is generated, if the given capability is invalid a \fIbadarg\fR error is generated.

.PP
This function does not work on Windows and will always generate a \fIbadarg\fR exception.

.PP
Example:

.IP
.nf
%% Set the foreground color to 3
1> io_ansi:tput("setaf",[3]).
<<"\\e[33m">>
%% Move the cursor up 2 spaces
2> io_ansi:tput("cuu",[2]).
<<"\\e[2A">>
%% Move the cursor down 1 space
3> io_ansi:tput("cud1").
<<"\\n">>
%% unsupported capability
4> io_ansi:tput("slm").
** exception error: {enotsup,"slm"}
     in function  io_ansi:tput/2
%% unknown capability
5> io_ansi:tput("foobar").
** exception error: {einval,"foobar",[]}
     in function  io_ansi:tput/2

.fi


